<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!-- Merged into the macOS bundle by tauri-build. Without these usage
     strings macOS silently denies the resource (the capture stream runs and
     delivers pure zeros — no error, no prompt), which reads as "audio
     route active, no sound". In `just dev` the permission attaches to the
     terminal that launched cargo instead; the bundle needs its own.

     NSLocalNetworkUsageDescription is the same trap one layer down: on
     macOS 14+ an app must hold the Local Network permission to reach peers
     on the LAN, and the OS only ever prompts for it when this usage string
     is present. The mesh's fastest path is a direct host↔host ICE pair
     (local IPs); without the permission those candidates are silently
     dropped, so a same-network peer is unreachable unless a TURN relay
     happens to be available — which reads as "can't connect to the other
     machines" with no error. The string makes macOS prompt (and lists the
     app under Settings ▸ Privacy & Security ▸ Local Network), so the user
     can actually grant it. -->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>NSMicrophoneUsageDescription</key>
  <string>AllMyStuff streams this machine's microphone to the devices you wire it to.</string>
  <key>NSCameraUsageDescription</key>
  <string>AllMyStuff streams this machine's cameras to the devices you wire them to.</string>
  <key>NSLocalNetworkUsageDescription</key>
  <string>AllMyStuff connects directly to your other machines on the local network to stream screens, audio, and files between them.</string>
</dict>
</plist>
